<HEAD><TITLE>Clinton's Health Plan</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>Chomsky on Clinton's Health Plan</H1>
<P>August 27, 1994

<P><TABLE WIDTH=66%><TR><TD>
<I>This is from Z magazine's ZBBS (now part of LBBS which is co-sponsored with the Nation and many many others; email a message to</I> <A HREF="mailto:lbbs-info@igc.apc.org">lbbs-info@igc.apc.org</A><I>). Chomsky was replying to a message by ZBBS/LBBS subscriber Charles Wilkins.</I>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<P><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><B>Charles Wilkins:</B> I am wondering. Clinton is so lame, is he merely trying to offer something so pitiful that no one will support it, and health care will go away again?

<P>If he wanted a serious plan, surely by organizing the populace he could win one. Maybe not ideal. But a lot better than anything that has even been discussed, much less put on the docket.

<P>I wonder what you think, professor Chomsky...</FONT>

<P><B>Noam Chomsky:</B> In my opinion, Clinton's been trying to put through a health plan that will satisfy the demands of the huge insurance companies and will place them, and other huge organizations under business control, in a position to control the rising health costs that are becoming a serious burden for US-based corporate power. The actual plan he proposed might or might not be an improvement over the current system, but that's not the driving factor. If it were, he would have proposed a plan of the sort that has long been favored by a majority or substantial pluralities -- even though it is barely discussed in the mainstream: what is called here a "single payer plan," a cover term for some sort of tax-based system that guarantees health care. That is not in the cards, though there is quite compelling evidence that it would be far more efficient, would involve much less bureaucracy and needless cost, and even happens to be quite popular among the general population, though not the narrow sectors that matter. The only plans that are being seriously considered are radically regressive "soak the poor" plans that leave the huge insurance corporations in power, so the taxpayer will have to fund their massive profits, internal bureaucracies and inefficiencies, ludicrous executive salaries and perks, advertising, etc. -- while watching them work as best they can to reduce health care to the minimum (after all, they are not charities: their task is to make profit). A still better plan, not even being discussed, would change priorities radically to preventive care, overcoming social and infrastructure factors that cause disease and suffering, and so on.

<P>Clinton's attempt to steer through a program that meets his priorities has, not surprisingly, met difficulties from all sides. I agree with you that he could organize public support for a "serious plan," but that would not be acceptable to the power systems that he primarily serves -- though it is intriguing that the hopelessly inefficient semi-privatized system now operating has become so harmful to business interests that even "Business Week" came out in support (more or less) for a "single payer" plan.

</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
