<HEAD><TITLE>The Middle East Hour 11/1/91</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER> <TABLE BORDER><TR><TD><A HREF="../index.html">Archive</A> | <A HREF="/">New World Media</A> | <A HREF="http://www.lbbs.org/">ZNet</A></TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR WIDTH=30%>

<H2>Counterpoint Interview</H2>

<P>November 1, 1991

<P><TABLE WIDTH=66%><TR><TD>
<I>This interview was broadcast originally on WNTR, NewsTalk Radio, Washington, DC on "The Middle East Hour" on Nov 1, 1991, hosted by Mark Bruzonsky Chairperson, Jewish Committee on the Middle East (JCOME) and Former Washington Representative, World Jewish Congress; guests were: Professor Noam Chomsky at MIT, Former Major General Matti Peled in Israel, Professor Riad Malki in Occupied Palestine, and Professor Hisham Ahmed from Grand Forks, North Dakota</I>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<P><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><B>JCOME:</B> Welcome to this first edition of the Middle East Hour sponsored by the Jewish Committee on the Middle East -- JCOME. Each week we will try to do something rather novel -- to bring you a tough, no-nonsense, hard-hitting and fast-paced discussion of what is really taking place in the Middle East and what the realities of American involvement with that crucial region really are. These realities are quite different and often at odds with how these matters are usually discussed here in this country. Indeed, that is why the Jewish Committee on the Middle East has decided to sponsor this program and to bring you what we consider a very honest and candid discussion of the realities of the situation. More about the Middle East Hour and more about the Jewish Committee on the Middle East as we proceed this hour.

<P>Today we have a unique lineup of Middle East experts for you. Professor Noam Chomsky is standing by at his office at M.I.T. Former Israeli General Matti Peled is in Jerusalem. Professor Riyad Malki, a Palestinian professor, is in the West Bank, and Professor Hisham Ahmed, a visiting professor, also from Palestine, is at the University of North Dakota.

<P>We couldn't have a better person to begin this discussion than Professor Noam Chomsky at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He is famous both as a linguist and a political analyst. He is a personal friend. And his perspective on these issues is always unique and penetrating. Noam, are you on line?</FONT>

<P><B>Noam Chomsky:</B> Yes, I am.

<P><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><B>JCOME:</B>We've just been through three very historic days, and I suspect you, like all of us, have been watching in awe what's been going on in Madrid. What are your thoughts as this conference comes to an end? And would you discuss your perspective on what American policies really are? Why did the United States bring this conference about in the first place?</FONT>

<P><B>Chomsky:</B> Well, I guess I must be one of the few who has not been watching in awe. Anyway, I haven't. I think that there are two parts to your question, as I understand it. One is whether the current American policies -- the policies of the Bush Administration --  are a new departure in any sense, or whether they simply continue U.S. Government policies towards the region.  The second is --  given that at least something is new; namely, there's a conference  -- why the efforts to have it now?

<P>Now, in my view, the policies of the U.S. Government insofar as they have any evidence about this (maybe something is going on in secret)...but insofar as there is any public evidence, the policies of the Bush Administration are basically those that the U.S. Government has been pursuing for about twenty years.

<P>In this respect, the United States has been in virtual diplomatic isolation. If you look at votes in the United Nations or other forums and so on, you find that it's the U.S. and Israel, essentially, against the world, and on two major issues: exactly the issues that come up annually at the United Nations and lead to votes of 144 to 2, as it was last December, and so on all the way back. One issue is whether there will be an internationally sponsored peace process. The United States has always been opposed to that. Every call for an international conference the United States has blocked, as last December in the 144 to 2 vote. And the reason for that is that the United States position is that this is U.S. turf. Nobody else is allowed to interfere. Henry Kissinger once put it privately (later declassified) that a major goal of his policy was to keep Europe and Japan out of diplomacy. Anybody with an independent voice must be kept out. Now in this current case, Gorbachev is permitted in. But that's because it is recognized that he is powerless and that the Soviet Union doesn't exist, and it will do anything the United States says. Therefore, they're allowed in. But apart from that, any independent force is not permitted. That's one reason why the U.S. has blocked the strong international effort for a peace process for many years; actually, twenty years.

<P>The second issue has to do with the form of the settlement. And on that the United States has been adamant that the Palestinians have no right of national self-determination. That has been the U.S. policy for many years. The U.S. has had to veto resolutions at the Security Council. It had to vote alone, or along with Israel, over and over at the General Assembly. It had to block other initiatives, always for the same reason. The U.S. position has been and remains that the Palestinians do not have a right of self-determination. But the Israeli client of the United States should have control over what it wants in the Occupied Territories.  And those remain the U.S.  positions as far as we know. They were made very explicit by James Baker, well before the Iraq War, in the early stage of the negotiations that led to these meetings -- in October and December, 1989, well before the war in the Gulf, at the time when the U.S.-P.L.O. dialogue was moving along supposedly unimpeded. At that time, the Baker Plan came out and Baker -- both in the plan and in his accompanying comments -- made it explicit and clear that the only proposal under discussion...his only effort was to move forward the implementation of what is called the Shamir Plan.

<P>Now, the Shamir Plan is actually a coalition plan of the two major Israeli parties. So it would be more accurate to call it the Shamir-Peres Plan -- the Likud-Labor Plan. And Baker stated openly that our only policy is to implement this plan. The Baker five points stated that, in accordance with the plan, some Palestinians might be admitted to negotiations if the U.S. and Israel approved of them. In other words, Palestinians could not choose their own representatives. His plan then stipulated that any Palestinians allowed to participate by the United States would be limited to discussing the modalities of implementation of the Shamir Plan.  They were not allowed to discuss any other issue.

<P><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><B>JCOME:</B>Well, Noam, what I hear you saying is that what we're witnessing today is really just a continuation of the step-by-step diplomacy that really goes back fifteen to twenty years to the Kissinger period. What is the United States trying to bring about? We've had three days of conference. Surely, there must be some goal.</FONT>

<P><B>Chomsky:</B> Yes, there is a goal. The old goal is, first, to ensure that the settlement is unilaterally determined by the United States without interference from anyone else...and that's what's happening in Madrid...and, secondly, to bring about the long-term goals that the U.S. has always favored. These goals are essentially the traditional position of the Israeli Labor Party, as stated in the Shamir-Peres plan, that Jordan is already a Palestinian state (so there is no issue of Palestinian self-determination), and that with regard to the occupied territories (the Gaza Strip and the West Bank)... Here there is a divergence within Israel between the two major parties, and the U.S. has typically tended toward the Labor position, and still does. That position is that Israel should essentially take what it wants from the occupied territories.  It should take control of the resources like the water. It should take the pleasant suburbs around a vastly expanded Jerusalem. It should take the usable land. But it should _not_ take responsibility for the bulk of the population. The bulk of the population in the West Bank should be under, preferably, Jordanian administration, or alternatively, under what's called "autonomy", meaning they can run local affairs, set tax rates, collect garbage and so on. But _not_ move toward self-determination.

<P>And that remains the U.S. position. In fact, it's built into the structure of the conference. Since the U.S. runs the conference unilaterally, it's been able to impose that potential settlement as its outcome.

<P>[end of text; interview continues]


<P><HR WIDTH=30%>
