<!--HTML: Tom Lane MOD 1/11/97-->

<HEAD><TITLE>About the Chomsky Archive</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="white" LINK="4F4F87" VLINK="72348F" ALINK="4C8F4D">

<H2 ALIGN=center>History of the Archive</H1>


<P>The Noam Chomsky Archive began as an effort to consolidate all of Chomsky's work available in the public domain. The original archive, put together by <A HREF="mailto:jimmer+@cmu.edu">Jimmer Endres</A>, contained many of the interviews, lectures, and Z Magazine articles, and even then constituted over 3 megabytes. Originally located on a different server, it moved to the <A HREF="http://www.lbbs.org/">ZNet</A> site in 1995, where it sat alongside two major publishers of Chomsky's work, <A HREF="http://www.lbbs.org/zmag/index.htm">Z Magazine</A> and <A HREF="http://www.lbbs.org/sep/sep.htm">South End Press</A>. You can still access that version of the archive by going to it directly at <A HREF="http://www.lbbs.org/archive/index.htm">http://www.lbbs.org/archive/index.htm</A>.

<P>During this time, <A HREF="mailto:jeremy@allaire.com">Jeremy Allaire</A> worked with Noam, Noam's wife Carol, and several publishers to make <A HREF="http://www.worldmedia.com/">New World Media</A> the on-line publisher of several of Chomsky's books. At the beginning of 1996, ZNet and New World Media came together to co-sponsor the new and improved Noam Chomsky Archive.

<P>The current archive features all of the original material reformatted in HTML, plus books from Common Courage Press, Hill and Wang, Odonian Press, and <A HREF="http://www.lbbs.org/sep/sep.htm">South End Press</A>. Altogether it consumes nearly eight megabytes. <A HREF="mailto:tl001c@uhura.cc.rochester.edu">Tom Lane</A> maintains the current archive, and welcomes your comments.

<P>The publishers wish for this material to reach and inspire as many people as possible, but they also must continue to generate revenue. As such, if you enjoy what you see, please consider purchasing a hard copy of the book or a subscription to <A HREF="http://www.lbbs.org/zmag/index.htm">Z Magazine</A>. (If you enjoy this material, you will certainly enjoy Z Magazine, which Chomsky regularly writes for.) Some of the larger books are broken into segments of about eight paragraphs each to offer a little bit of futher incentive to purchase the hard copy. However, feel free to excerpt portions of the work (in e-mail, newsgroup posts, etc.), as long as you include the publisher information and a line saying "From the Noam Chomsky Archive, http://www.worldmedia.com/archive/". If you wish to excerpt more than 500 words, or have any questions about the copyright, please contact the publisher.

<P>In the future the archive will feature:

<UL>
<LI>More books

<LI>RealAudio selections from speeches

<LI>Chomsky's speaking schedule

<LI>Search capabilities

<LI>A complete index

<LI>Hopefully much more!
</UL>


<CENTER>
